<!-- ===== SECTION 1: WHAT IS METABOLISM ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec1">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">01</span> What Is Metabolism?</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Metabolism is the word we use for all the chemical reactions happening inside you right now. If you ate breakfast this morning, your body is currently breaking those molecules apart, pulling out the stored energy, and using that energy to do everything — move your muscles, fire your brain signals, grow new cells, keep your heart beating.</p>
    <div class="callout analogy">
      <div class="callout-label">Think of It This Way</div>
      <p>Imagine your body is a city. Metabolism is everything the city does: the power plants making electricity, the trucks delivering materials, the factories building things, the garbage trucks hauling away waste. Glycolysis is the main power plant — the one almost every other system depends on.</p>
    </div>
    <p>Metabolism has two sides. <strong>Catabolism</strong> means breaking things down to release energy — like taking apart a Lego set. <strong>Anabolism</strong> means building things up using that energy — like using Legos to build something new. Glycolysis is catabolism: it breaks apart sugar to release energy.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Idea</div>
      <p>The energy currency of the cell is a molecule called ATP (adenosine triphosphate). Almost everything your cells do requires ATP. Glycolysis is one way your cells make it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">Tracking Energy In and Out</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>You eat a piece of bread. The starch in bread is made of long chains of glucose. Your digestive system breaks the starch into individual glucose molecules. Those glucose molecules enter your cells. Glycolysis then breaks each glucose into two smaller molecules called pyruvate, capturing some of the energy as ATP. Where did that energy come from? It was stored in the chemical bonds of glucose — bonds that were originally built by a plant using sunlight.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq1a">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Which word describes breaking molecules apart to release energy?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1a',this,false)">Anabolism</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1a',this,true)">Catabolism</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1a',this,false)">Metabolism</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1a',this,false)">Synthesis</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq1a-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>Metabolism encompasses the complete set of biochemical reactions within a cell. It divides into two broad categories: <strong>catabolism</strong> (breaking complex molecules into simpler ones, releasing energy) and <strong>anabolism</strong> (building complex molecules from simpler ones, requiring energy). These two arms are interlinked — the energy released by catabolism powers anabolic reactions.</p>
    <p>The universal energy carrier in biology is <strong>ATP</strong>. When cells need to do work — contract a muscle, build a protein, pump ions — they hydrolyze ATP to ADP plus inorganic phosphate, releasing about 7.3 kcal/mol of free energy. Glycolysis and the rest of cellular respiration exist primarily to regenerate ATP from ADP.</p>
    <div class="callout analogy">
      <div class="callout-label">Analogy</div>
      <p>Think of ATP as a rechargeable battery. Catabolism (including glycolysis) recharges the battery. Anabolism and cell work drain it. The cell is constantly cycling through charge-discharge cycles, processing roughly 40 kg of ATP per day in an active adult — even though total body ATP at any moment is only about 250 mg.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">ATP Hydrolysis</div>
      ATP + H&#8322;O → ADP + Pᵢ + ~7.3 kcal/mol (free energy released)
    </div>
    <p>Glycolysis sits at the top of metabolism's hierarchy. It is the universal gateway: all carbohydrates, and many other molecules, funnel through it. Its product, pyruvate, then routes to the Krebs cycle (aerobic conditions) or fermentation (anaerobic conditions), making glycolysis a central traffic director for cellular energy.</p>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq1b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">An athlete's muscle cells run low on ATP during intense sprinting. Which process is primarily responsible for regenerating that ATP fastest?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1b',this,false)">Anabolism of proteins</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1b',this,false)">Fatty acid synthesis</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1b',this,true)">Catabolism via glycolysis (and fermentation)</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1b',this,false)">Oxidative phosphorylation only</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq1b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>Metabolism is the integrated network of enzyme-catalyzed reactions that cells use to extract, store, and deploy free energy. The central concept is Gibbs free energy (ΔG): reactions proceed spontaneously when ΔG &lt; 0. Cells couple thermodynamically unfavorable reactions (ΔG &gt; 0) to favorable ones — most often the hydrolysis of ATP (ΔG°' = −7.3 kcal/mol, actual cellular ΔG ≈ −10 to −14 kcal/mol due to low [ADP] and [Pᵢ] relative to [ATP]).</p>
    <p>The metabolic map organizes into interacting pathways: glycolysis, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, the citric acid cycle, oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid β-oxidation, fatty acid synthesis, amino acid catabolism, urea cycle, and nucleotide metabolism. These are tightly regulated by allosteric mechanisms, hormonal signals (insulin/glucagon axis), and substrate availability. Glycolysis is the entry point for glucose catabolism and feeds directly into gluconeogenesis (reverse), the PPP (branch at G6P), and the Krebs cycle (via pyruvate).</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Standard Free Energy of ATP Hydrolysis</div>
      ATP + H&#8322;O → ADP + Pᵢ    ΔG°' = −7.3 kcal/mol
      Cellular ΔG ≈ −10 to −14 kcal/mol (due to mass action ratio)
    </div>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Concept</div>
      <p>The actual ΔG of ATP hydrolysis in the cell is significantly more negative than ΔG°' because [ATP]/([ADP][Pᵢ]) is maintained far from equilibrium — the cell continuously regenerates ATP to keep this ratio high. Glycolysis and oxidative phosphorylation together sustain this disequilibrium.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical Connection</div>
      <p>Warburg effect: cancer cells preferentially use aerobic glycolysis (glycolysis even in the presence of oxygen) rather than oxidative phosphorylation. This produces less ATP per glucose but generates biosynthetic precursors (ribose-5-phosphate via PPP, serine via 3-phosphoglycerate) needed for rapid proliferation. This phenomenon underpins PET scanning (FDG uptake) and is a target of many anti-cancer strategies.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq1c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">The actual cellular ΔG of ATP hydrolysis (−10 to −14 kcal/mol) is more negative than ΔG°' (−7.3 kcal/mol) primarily because:</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1c',this,false)">Temperature in the cell is higher than 25°C</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1c',this,true)">The [ATP]/([ADP][Pᵢ]) ratio is maintained far above equilibrium</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1c',this,false)">Enzymes lower the activation energy of hydrolysis</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq1c',this,false)">Cellular pH is lower than 7.0</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq1c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 2: OVERVIEW OF GLYCOLYSIS ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec2">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">02</span> Overview of Glycolysis</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Glycolysis happens in the liquid part of the cell called the cytoplasm (not inside any organelle — just floating in the cell fluid). It takes one molecule of glucose (a 6-carbon sugar) and breaks it into two molecules of pyruvate (each 3 carbons). The whole process is ten steps, and a team of enzymes does each one.</p>
    <div class="callout analogy">
      <div class="callout-label">Think of It This Way</div>
      <p>Think of glucose as a $10 bill. To use it, you need to break it into smaller bills. The first half of glycolysis spends two $1 bills (2 ATP) to split the $10 into two $5 bills. The second half converts each $5 into change — you get four $1 bills back (4 ATP) plus some "savings bonds" (NADH) you'll cash in later. Net profit: 2 ATP per glucose.</p>
    </div>
    <p>Glycolysis has two main phases. The first phase — steps 1 through 5 — spends energy to prepare glucose for splitting. The second phase — steps 6 through 10 — harvests energy from the resulting molecules. You put in 2 ATP and get out 4 ATP, for a net gain of 2 ATP. You also make 2 NADH, which are electron carriers that the cell uses for more energy production later.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Glycolysis Summary</div>
      Glucose + 2 ADP + 2 Pᵢ + 2 NAD⁺ → 2 Pyruvate + 2 ATP + 2 NADH + 2 H⁺ + 2 H₂O
    </div>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Numbers</div>
      <p>Input: 1 glucose, 2 ATP spent. Output: 2 pyruvate, 4 ATP made (net +2 ATP), 2 NADH. Location: cytoplasm.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq2a">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Where in the cell does glycolysis take place?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2a',this,false)">Mitochondria</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2a',this,false)">Nucleus</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2a',this,true)">Cytoplasm (cytosol)</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2a',this,false)">Endoplasmic reticulum</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq2a-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>Glycolysis is a ten-step cytosolic pathway that converts one glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆) into two molecules of pyruvate (C₃H₄O₃). It is divided into an <strong>energy investment phase</strong> (steps 1–5) that consumes 2 ATP per glucose, and an <strong>energy payoff phase</strong> (steps 6–10) that generates 4 ATP and 2 NADH per glucose. Net yield: 2 ATP and 2 NADH per glucose.</p>
    <p>Glycolysis requires no oxygen. This makes it the only energy-generating pathway available to anaerobic organisms, and it is also the first step in aerobic respiration. The pathway is universal across all domains of life — the same ten steps occur in bacteria, yeast, plants, and humans, which speaks to how ancient and essential it is.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Balanced Net Equation</div>
      Glucose + 2 NAD⁺ + 2 ADP + 2 Pᵢ → 2 Pyruvate + 2 NADH + 2 H⁺ + 2 ATP + 2 H₂O
    </div>
    <div class="callout mnemonic">
      <div class="callout-label">Mnemonic — The 10 Enzymes in Order</div>
      <p>"Hexokinase Phosphoglucose-isomerase Phosphofructokinase Aldolase TPI GAPDH PGK PGAM Enolase Pyruvate kinase"</p>
      <p>Memory trick for the first three (the regulation checkpoints): <strong>H-P-P</strong> = "Happy Pathways Produce."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq2b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">A cell produces 4 ATP during glycolysis but has a net gain of only 2 ATP. Why?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2b',this,false)">Two ATP are lost as heat during the payoff phase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2b',this,true)">Two ATP are consumed during the energy investment phase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2b',this,false)">The cell uses 2 ATP to transport pyruvate to the mitochondria</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2b',this,false)">Two ATP are used to regenerate NAD⁺</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq2b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>Glycolysis (from Greek: glukus = sweet, lysis = splitting) converts glucose to two molecules of pyruvate through ten sequential enzyme-catalyzed reactions, all occurring in the cytosol. The pathway is divided into a preparatory (priming) phase and a payoff phase. Overall thermodynamics are favorable (ΔG°' = −18.5 kcal/mol for the net reaction), but several individual steps are close to equilibrium while three are highly exergonic and effectively irreversible under physiological conditions — these are the regulated steps.</p>
    <p>Three enzymes catalyze essentially irreversible steps and are subject to allosteric regulation: <strong>hexokinase</strong> (step 1), <strong>phosphofructokinase-1</strong> (step 3, the primary rate-limiting step), and <strong>pyruvate kinase</strong> (step 10). The remaining seven steps are near-equilibrium and reversible — they are shared with gluconeogenesis, which uses distinct enzymes only at the three irreversible steps.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Net Glycolytic Equation (Standard Conditions)</div>
      Glucose + 2 NAD⁺ + 2 ADP + 2 Pᵢ → 2 Pyruvate + 2 NADH + 2 H⁺ + 2 ATP + 2 H₂O
      ΔG°' = −18.5 kcal/mol  |  Actual ΔG in vivo ≈ −28 kcal/mol
    </div>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">The Three Irreversible Steps</div>
      <p>Step 1 (hexokinase), Step 3 (PFK-1), Step 10 (pyruvate kinase). These are bypassed in gluconeogenesis by glucose-6-phosphatase, fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase, and the pyruvate carboxylase/PEPCK pair respectively. Knowing these bypass enzymes is essential for understanding metabolic regulation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq2c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Which enzyme catalyzes the primary rate-limiting step of glycolysis and is the most important regulatory point?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2c',this,false)">Hexokinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2c',this,true)">Phosphofructokinase-1 (PFK-1)</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2c',this,false)">Pyruvate kinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq2c',this,false)">Aldolase</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq2c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 3: PHASE 1 ENERGY INVESTMENT ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec3">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">03</span> Phase 1: Energy Investment (Steps 1–5)</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>The first five steps of glycolysis spend energy to prepare glucose for splitting. Think of it like priming a pump — you put energy in now so you can get more energy out later.</p>
    <h3>Step 1 — Glucose gets a phosphate tag</h3>
    <p>The enzyme <strong>hexokinase</strong> grabs a phosphate group from ATP and attaches it to glucose, making glucose-6-phosphate. This does two things: it uses one ATP (energy cost), and it traps glucose inside the cell. Once glucose has a phosphate tag, it cannot leave through the cell membrane.</p>
    <h3>Step 2 — Rearrangement</h3>
    <p>The enzyme <strong>phosphoglucose isomerase</strong> reshapes glucose-6-phosphate into a slightly different form called fructose-6-phosphate. No energy is used — this is just rearranging the atoms into a shape that works better for the next step.</p>
    <h3>Step 3 — Another phosphate tag (the big commitment)</h3>
    <p><strong>Phosphofructokinase (PFK)</strong> adds a second phosphate, spending another ATP to make fructose-1,6-bisphosphate. This is the most important step in the whole pathway — once this happens, the molecule is committed to glycolysis. The cell uses this step as its main "throttle" to speed up or slow down energy production.</p>
    <h3>Step 4 — The split</h3>
    <p><strong>Aldolase</strong> breaks fructose-1,6-bisphosphate in half. You now have two 3-carbon molecules. One is called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P) and can continue directly. The other is dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).</p>
    <h3>Step 5 — Interconversion</h3>
    <p><strong>Triose phosphate isomerase (TPI)</strong> converts DHAP into another G3P. Now you have two G3P molecules — both able to continue through phase 2. This enzyme is so efficient that it is considered nearly perfect.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Phase 1 Summary</div>
      <p>Input: 1 glucose, 2 ATP. Output: 2 G3P molecules. Cost paid. Now ready for energy harvest.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">Why Does the Cell Spend ATP First?</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>Question: The cell already wants energy — so why does it spend 2 ATP in phase 1?</p>
        <p>Answer: Phosphorylation (adding phosphate groups) does two important things. First, it traps glucose inside the cell — phosphorylated molecules are charged and cannot cross membranes. Second, it activates the glucose molecule — the phosphate groups make the molecule more reactive and easier for enzymes in phase 2 to break apart. It is an investment that pays off 2-to-1 in phase 2.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq3a">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Which step of glycolysis is considered the "point of no return" that commits glucose to the pathway?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3a',this,false)">Step 1 — Hexokinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3a',this,false)">Step 2 — Phosphoglucose isomerase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3a',this,true)">Step 3 — Phosphofructokinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3a',this,false)">Step 4 — Aldolase</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq3a-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>The investment phase phosphorylates glucose twice (using 2 ATP) and cleaves the resulting hexose bisphosphate into two interconvertible triose phosphates. All five reactions occur in the cytosol.</p>
    <table class="step-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Enzyme</th><th>Reaction</th><th>Energy</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">1</td><td class="enzyme-name">Hexokinase</td><td>Glucose → Glucose-6-P</td><td class="energy-cell energy-invest">−1 ATP</td><td>Traps glucose in cell; inhibited by G6P (product inhibition)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">2</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglucose isomerase</td><td>G6P → Fructose-6-P</td><td>0</td><td>Isomerization; near-equilibrium, reversible</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">3</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphofructokinase-1</td><td>F6P → Fructose-1,6-bisP</td><td class="energy-cell energy-invest">−1 ATP</td><td>Rate-limiting; key allosteric regulation point</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">4</td><td class="enzyme-name">Aldolase</td><td>F-1,6-bisP → DHAP + G3P</td><td>0</td><td>Splits the 6C sugar into two 3C pieces</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">5</td><td class="enzyme-name">Triose phosphate isomerase</td><td>DHAP → G3P</td><td>0</td><td>Near-perfect enzyme; converts DHAP so only G3P continues</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="callout pitfall">
      <div class="callout-label">Common Mistake</div>
      <p>After step 5, you have TWO G3P molecules per original glucose. Everything from step 6 onward happens TWICE per glucose — so all yields (ATP, NADH) in phase 2 are per G3P but must be doubled for the per-glucose count.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">Hexokinase vs. Glucokinase</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>Hexokinase (found in most cells) has a high affinity for glucose and is inhibited by its own product, G6P. This makes it self-regulating: when the cell is full of G6P, hexokinase slows down.</p>
        <p>Liver and pancreatic beta cells have a special isoform called <strong>glucokinase (hexokinase IV)</strong>. It has a much lower affinity for glucose (Km ≈ 10 mM vs. 0.1 mM for hexokinase) and is NOT inhibited by G6P. This means the liver only phosphorylates glucose rapidly when blood glucose is high — serving as a glucose sensor. This distinction is clinically important in understanding diabetes and liver glucose metabolism.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq3b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Triose phosphate isomerase converts DHAP to G3P. After step 5, how many G3P molecules are available for phase 2 from one glucose?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3b',this,false)">1 — only the G3P from aldolase continues</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3b',this,true)">2 — both DHAP and G3P are converted to G3P</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3b',this,false)">3 — aldolase makes three fragments</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3b',this,false)">4 — each phosphate group generates one G3P</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq3b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>The preparatory phase commits glucose to the glycolytic pathway through sequential phosphorylation and structural rearrangement, culminating in cleavage to two glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate molecules.</p>
    <table class="step-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Enzyme</th><th>ΔG°' (kcal/mol)</th><th>Mechanism / Regulation</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">1</td><td class="enzyme-name">Hexokinase (I–III) / Glucokinase (IV)</td><td class="energy-cell energy-invest">−4.0</td><td>Mg²⁺-dependent phosphotransfer; HK inhibited by G6P (product); GK (liver) not inhibited by G6P, sigmoidal kinetics, Km ≈ 10 mM. Irreversible.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">2</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglucose isomerase</td><td>+0.4</td><td>Ring opening; enediol intermediate; near equilibrium (ΔG ≈ 0 in vivo). Reversible — shared with gluconeogenesis.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">3</td><td class="enzyme-name">PFK-1</td><td class="energy-cell energy-invest">−3.4</td><td>Key regulatory step. Allosteric activators: AMP, ADP, F-2,6-bisP. Inhibitors: ATP (high conc.), citrate, H⁺. F-2,6-bisP (made by PFK-2, activated by insulin) is the most potent activator. Irreversible.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">4</td><td class="enzyme-name">Aldolase (class I in animals)</td><td>+5.7 (near 0 in vivo)</td><td>Schiff base mechanism with Lys residue. Pulls the equilibrium by mass action (G3P and DHAP continuously consumed).</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">5</td><td class="enzyme-name">Triose phosphate isomerase</td><td>+1.8 (≈0 in vivo)</td><td>Enediol intermediate; catalytic perfection (kcat/Km near diffusion limit, ~10⁸ M⁻¹s⁻¹). Prevents DHAP accumulation.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical: TPI Deficiency</div>
      <p>Triose phosphate isomerase deficiency is a rare autosomal recessive disorder. DHAP accumulates and cannot be converted to G3P, leading to hemolytic anemia (red cells are highly glycolysis-dependent) and progressive neuromuscular deterioration. It is uniformly fatal in early childhood. It illustrates how even "near-equilibrium" enzymes can be rate-limiting when absent.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">PFK-1 Regulation: Integrating Energy Status</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>Consider a hepatocyte in two states: (A) fed state (high ATP, high insulin) and (B) fasted state (low ATP, high glucagon).</p>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">A</span><span>Fed: Insulin activates PFK-2 → elevated F-2,6-bisP → PFK-1 highly active → glycolysis proceeds. Simultaneously, high ATP allosterically inhibits PFK-1 at a separate site, but F-2,6-bisP overrides this inhibition.</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">B</span><span>Fasted: Glucagon activates PKA → phosphorylates PFK-2/FBPase-2 bifunctional enzyme → FBPase-2 domain active → F-2,6-bisP drops → PFK-1 inhibited → glycolysis slows, gluconeogenesis favored.</span></div>
        <p>This is a textbook example of hormonal control via second messenger (cAMP) regulating a key metabolic branch point.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq3c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-bisP) is elevated in the fed state. What is its primary effect on PFK-1?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3c',this,false)">Inhibits PFK-1, slowing glycolysis to conserve ATP</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3c',this,true)">Allosterically activates PFK-1, even in the presence of high ATP</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3c',this,false)">Has no effect on PFK-1; it only regulates PFK-2</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq3c',this,false)">Covalently modifies PFK-1 via phosphorylation</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq3c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 4: PHASE 2 ENERGY PAYOFF ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec4">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">04</span> Phase 2: Energy Payoff (Steps 6–10)</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>This is where the cell gets its money back — and then some. Each G3P molecule goes through five more steps that pull out energy in the form of ATP and NADH. Remember: you have TWO G3P molecules from every glucose, so everything here happens twice.</p>
    <h3>Step 6 — Making NADH and setting up ATP</h3>
    <p><strong>GAPDH</strong> (a big-named enzyme) oxidizes G3P and loads the energy onto a carrier molecule NAD⁺, converting it to NADH. It also attaches an inorganic phosphate, creating a high-energy molecule called 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate.</p>
    <h3>Step 7 — First ATP made</h3>
    <p><strong>Phosphoglycerate kinase</strong> transfers the phosphate from 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate to ADP, making ATP. This is called substrate-level phosphorylation — ATP is made directly from a molecule, not from a membrane pump.</p>
    <h3>Steps 8 and 9 — Moving the phosphate</h3>
    <p>These two steps rearrange the molecule, moving the phosphate to a position where it has even more energy, creating a molecule called phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP). PEP is one of the highest-energy phosphate compounds in biology.</p>
    <h3>Step 10 — Final ATP and making pyruvate</h3>
    <p><strong>Pyruvate kinase</strong> transfers the phosphate from PEP to ADP, making the second ATP and releasing pyruvate. This is the end of glycolysis.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Phase 2 Yield (per G3P → doubled for glucose)</div>
      <p>Per G3P: 2 ATP, 1 NADH. Per glucose (×2): 4 ATP, 2 NADH. Minus the 2 ATP spent in phase 1 = net 2 ATP per glucose.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq4a">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">In phase 2 of glycolysis, ATP is made by directly transferring a phosphate from a sugar molecule to ADP. What is this type of ATP production called?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4a',this,false)">Oxidative phosphorylation</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4a',this,true)">Substrate-level phosphorylation</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4a',this,false)">Chemiosmosis</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4a',this,false)">Photophosphorylation</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq4a-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>The payoff phase oxidizes each G3P to pyruvate, producing ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation at steps 7 and 10, and NADH at step 6. Everything below is doubled for per-glucose totals.</p>
    <table class="step-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Enzyme</th><th>Reaction</th><th>Energy</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">6</td><td class="enzyme-name">GAPDH</td><td>G3P + NAD⁺ + Pᵢ → 1,3-BPG + NADH</td><td class="energy-cell energy-harvest">+NADH</td><td>Coupled oxidation and phosphorylation; produces high-energy acyl-phosphate bond</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">7</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglycerate kinase</td><td>1,3-BPG + ADP → 3-PG + ATP</td><td class="energy-cell energy-harvest">+1 ATP</td><td>Substrate-level phosphorylation; reversible (used in gluconeogenesis)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">8</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglycerate mutase</td><td>3-PG → 2-PG</td><td>0</td><td>Moves phosphate from C3 to C2; requires 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate cofactor</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">9</td><td class="enzyme-name">Enolase</td><td>2-PG → PEP + H₂O</td><td>0</td><td>Dehydration; creates very high-energy enol-phosphate bond in PEP</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">10</td><td class="enzyme-name">Pyruvate kinase</td><td>PEP + ADP → Pyruvate + ATP</td><td class="energy-cell energy-harvest">+1 ATP</td><td>Irreversible; allosterically regulated; produces final product pyruvate</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="callout pitfall">
      <div class="callout-label">Common Mistake</div>
      <p>Students often say glycolysis yields "2 ATP." Be precise: it produces 4 ATP and 2 NADH, with a net gain of 2 ATP because 2 were consumed in phase 1. On exam questions asking about "yield" vs. "net yield," these are different answers.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">Why is PEP Such a High-Energy Molecule?</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>Phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) has a very high phosphate transfer potential (ΔG°' of hydrolysis = −14.8 kcal/mol, compared to ATP at −7.3 kcal/mol). When pyruvate kinase transfers PEP's phosphate to ADP, it is thermodynamically very favorable. The reason PEP is so energetic is that when the phosphate leaves, pyruvate rearranges from an unstable enol form to a stable keto form — this tautomerization releases additional energy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq4b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">How many total NADH are produced during glycolysis of one glucose molecule?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4b',this,false)">1 NADH</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4b',this,true)">2 NADH</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4b',this,false)">4 NADH</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4b',this,false)">6 NADH</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq4b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>The payoff phase couples aldehyde oxidation to phosphorylation (step 6) and transfers the resulting high-energy phosphates to ADP at two substrate-level phosphorylation steps (steps 7 and 10). Key mechanistic and regulatory details are outlined below.</p>
    <table class="step-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Enzyme</th><th>ΔG°' (kcal/mol)</th><th>Mechanism / Clinical / Regulation</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">6</td><td class="enzyme-name">GAPDH</td><td>+1.5 (≈0 in vivo)</td><td>Cys-SH nucleophile forms thiohemiacetal; NAD⁺ oxidizes to NADH; inorganic phosphate attacks → acyl-phosphate (1,3-BPG). Inhibited by iodoacetate (and arsenate replaces Pᵢ, producing 1-arseno-3-PG that spontaneously hydrolyzes, uncoupling substrate-level phosphorylation — arsenic poisoning mechanism).</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">7</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglycerate kinase</td><td>−4.5</td><td>Mg²⁺-dependent; name is "backwards" — kinase adds phosphate to ADP from substrate. Reversible in gluconeogenesis (uses ATP to regenerate 1,3-BPG).</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">8</td><td class="enzyme-name">Phosphoglycerate mutase</td><td>+0.1</td><td>2,3-BPG-dependent (in vertebrates); enzyme itself is transiently phosphorylated. Note: 2,3-BPG in red cells is an important allosteric regulator of hemoglobin oxygen affinity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">9</td><td class="enzyme-name">Enolase</td><td>+0.4</td><td>Mg²⁺-dependent dehydration; inhibited by fluoride (F⁻ forms Mg-F-phosphate complex — used in dental products and to preserve blood glucose samples in fluoride tubes).</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="step-num-cell">10</td><td class="enzyme-name">Pyruvate kinase</td><td>−7.5</td><td>Irreversible; activated by F-1,6-bisP (feedforward activation), AMP; inhibited by ATP, alanine, acetyl-CoA. Liver PK-L is also inhibited by phosphorylation via PKA (glucagon signaling). PK-M2 isoform dominates in cancer cells (Warburg). Enol-keto tautomerization drives thermodynamics.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical: Pyruvate Kinase Deficiency</div>
      <p>PK deficiency is the most common enzymatic cause of hereditary non-spherocytic hemolytic anemia. RBCs have no mitochondria and depend entirely on glycolysis for ATP. PK deficiency → less ATP → pump failure → RBC lysis. Paradoxically, 2,3-BPG accumulates (step 8 backs up), which improves O₂ delivery to tissues — a partial metabolic compensation. Diagnosed by enzyme assay; treatment includes splenectomy and, in severe cases, transfusion or gene therapy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">Arsenic Poisoning and GAPDH</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">1</span><span>Arsenate (AsO₄³⁻) is a structural analog of inorganic phosphate (PO₄³⁻). It competes with Pᵢ at the GAPDH reaction (step 6).</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">2</span><span>GAPDH accepts arsenate, producing 1-arseno-3-phosphoglycerate instead of 1,3-BPG.</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">3</span><span>1-arseno-3-PG spontaneously hydrolyzes (unlike 1,3-BPG, which requires phosphoglycerate kinase).</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">4</span><span>Result: The energy from step 6 is wasted as heat rather than captured in 1,3-BPG. Step 7 (PGK) has no substrate → no ATP at step 7.</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">5</span><span>Net effect: Glycolysis uncoupled — glucose is still consumed, but ATP is not generated at step 7. Cells become energy-depleted. This explains why arsenic is acutely toxic.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq4c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">Fluoride preserves blood glucose in lab collection tubes by inhibiting which glycolytic enzyme?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4c',this,false)">GAPDH</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4c',this,false)">Pyruvate kinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4c',this,true)">Enolase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq4c',this,false)">Phosphoglycerate mutase</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq4c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 5: REGULATION ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec5">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">05</span> Regulation of Glycolysis</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Your body does not run glycolysis at full speed all the time. That would be wasteful. Instead, your cells have built-in speed controls. Three enzymes act as the main brakes and accelerators.</p>
    <p><strong>Hexokinase</strong> (step 1) slows down automatically when glucose-6-phosphate piles up — a simple "backup" sensor. <strong>PFK</strong> (step 3) is the main throttle. When you have lots of ATP, PFK slows down (no need to make more energy). When ATP is low and AMP is high, PFK speeds up. <strong>Pyruvate kinase</strong> (step 10) slows down when there is plenty of ATP and speeds up when the pathway is running fast.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Idea</div>
      <p>Think of it like a smart car engine. When the battery (ATP) is full, the engine (glycolysis) idles. When the battery drains (low ATP, high AMP), the engine revs up automatically.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>Glycolytic flux is primarily regulated at the three irreversible steps (1, 3, and 10). The most important regulatory enzyme is <strong>PFK-1</strong>.</p>
    <table class="step-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Enzyme</th><th>Activators</th><th>Inhibitors</th><th>Logic</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="enzyme-name">Hexokinase</td><td>Glucose</td><td>Glucose-6-phosphate (product inhibition)</td><td>Prevents glucose trapping when downstream is saturated</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="enzyme-name">PFK-1 (main throttle)</td><td>AMP, ADP, F-2,6-bisP</td><td>ATP (high), citrate, H⁺</td><td>Runs fast when energy is low; slows when energy is high or TCA intermediates accumulate</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="enzyme-name">Pyruvate kinase</td><td>F-1,6-bisP (feedforward), AMP</td><td>ATP, alanine, acetyl-CoA</td><td>Feedforward by its own upstream substrate; slows when amino acids available</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="callout mnemonic">
      <div class="callout-label">Mnemonic — PFK Inhibitors</div>
      <p>"<strong>A</strong>TP <strong>C</strong>uts <strong>H</strong>igh-speed Flux" = ATP, Citrate, H⁺ all inhibit PFK-1.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq5b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">High citrate levels inhibit PFK-1. Why does this make metabolic sense?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5b',this,false)">Citrate is toxic and must be removed before glycolysis can continue</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5b',this,true)">High citrate signals the TCA cycle is well-supplied and no more pyruvate is needed</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5b',this,false)">Citrate directly inhibits ATP synthesis</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5b',this,false)">Citrate is an activator of hexokinase, shifting control to step 1</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq5b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>Glycolytic regulation operates at three levels: substrate availability, allosteric control, and hormonal/covalent modification. The key regulatory node is PFK-1, subject to at least six allosteric effectors and positioned at the committed step.</p>
    <p><strong>F-2,6-bisP</strong> deserves special emphasis. It is synthesized by PFK-2 (a bifunctional enzyme) and is distinct from F-1,6-bisP. In the liver: insulin → PP2A activation → PFK-2 active → F-2,6-bisP high → PFK-1 active → glycolysis on. Glucagon → PKA → PFK-2 phosphorylated → FBPase-2 domain active → F-2,6-bisP drops → PFK-1 inhibited → gluconeogenesis favored. In muscle: F-2,6-bisP is less significant for regulation; AMP/ATP ratio dominates via AMP kinase (AMPK) signaling.</p>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical: AMPK and Metformin</div>
      <p>Metformin, the most prescribed diabetes drug, inhibits Complex I of the electron transport chain → ATP drops → AMP/ATP rises → AMPK activated → AMPK phosphorylates and inhibits ACC (fatty acid synthesis off) and stimulates GLUT4 translocation and glycolysis. AMPK is sometimes called the "fuel gauge" of the cell. This is why metformin lowers blood glucose without causing hypoglycemia — it does not directly stimulate insulin secretion.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq5c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">In hepatocytes, glucagon signaling leads to decreased glycolytic flux. The mechanism involves:</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5c',this,false)">Direct inhibition of hexokinase by glucagon receptor activation</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5c',this,true)">PKA phosphorylation of PFK-2 activating its FBPase-2 domain, lowering F-2,6-bisP</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5c',this,false)">Glucagon increasing AMP levels which inhibit PFK-1</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq5c',this,false)">Glucagon directly phosphorylating and inhibiting PFK-1</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq5c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 6: FATE OF PYRUVATE ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec6">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">06</span> Fate of Pyruvate</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Pyruvate is the final product of glycolysis. What happens to it next depends on whether your cells have oxygen available.</p>
    <p><strong>With oxygen:</strong> Pyruvate moves into the mitochondria and is converted to acetyl-CoA, which enters the Krebs cycle. This pathway extracts much more energy from glucose — about 30 more ATP per glucose beyond what glycolysis made.</p>
    <p><strong>Without oxygen (in muscles during intense exercise):</strong> Pyruvate is converted to lactate. This regenerates NAD⁺, which glycolysis needs to keep running. Without this "recycling," glycolysis would stop. This is why muscles can sprint even when you are out of breath.</p>
    <p><strong>In yeast:</strong> Pyruvate becomes ethanol and CO₂ — that is how beer and bread are made.</p>
    <div class="callout pitfall">
      <div class="callout-label">Common Misconception</div>
      <p>Lactic acid does NOT cause muscle soreness. The burn you feel during exercise is from acid (H⁺ ions), not lactate itself. The soreness you feel a day or two later (DOMS) is from muscle fiber damage — nothing to do with lactate.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>Pyruvate sits at a critical metabolic crossroads. Its route depends primarily on oxygen availability and the cell's energy state.</p>
    <p><strong>Aerobic conditions:</strong> The pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC) in the mitochondrial matrix converts pyruvate to acetyl-CoA + CO₂ + NADH. Acetyl-CoA feeds the TCA cycle. This is the high-yield path — the Krebs cycle and oxidative phosphorylation generate approximately 30–32 ATP per glucose.</p>
    <p><strong>Anaerobic (lactic acid fermentation):</strong> Lactate dehydrogenase converts pyruvate to lactate, oxidizing NADH back to NAD⁺. This NAD⁺ regeneration is the point — it lets glycolysis continue producing ATP when oxygen is absent. The lactate is exported and can be converted back to glucose in the liver (Cori cycle).</p>
    <p><strong>Alcoholic fermentation (yeast):</strong> Pyruvate decarboxylase removes CO₂, making acetaldehyde, then alcohol dehydrogenase reduces acetaldehyde to ethanol using NADH → NAD⁺.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Pyruvate Dehydrogenase Reaction</div>
      Pyruvate + NAD⁺ + CoA → Acetyl-CoA + CO₂ + NADH  (ΔG°' = −8 kcal/mol)
    </div>
    <div class="callout mnemonic">
      <div class="callout-label">Mnemonic — PDC Cofactors</div>
      <p>"<strong>T</strong>ender <strong>L</strong>oving <strong>C</strong>are <strong>F</strong>or <strong>N</strong>ancy" = TPP (B1), Lipoic acid, CoA (B5), FAD (B2), NAD⁺ (B3). Five cofactors from five vitamins.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>The pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC) is a massive multi-enzyme complex (~10 MDa) residing in the mitochondrial matrix. It consists of E1 (pyruvate decarboxylase, requires TPP), E2 (dihydrolipoamide acetyltransferase, requires lipoic acid and CoA), and E3 (dihydrolipoamide dehydrogenase, requires FAD and NAD⁺). The complex is regulated by phosphorylation: PDK (pyruvate dehydrogenase kinase) phosphorylates and inactivates E1; PDP (phosphatase) reactivates it.</p>
    <p>PDK is activated by acetyl-CoA, NADH, ATP (signals of energy excess — "no more input needed"). PDK is inhibited by pyruvate, CoA, NAD⁺, ADP (signals of low energy — "need more acetyl-CoA"). In the fed state, insulin activates PDP → PDC active. In fasting, glucagon/catecholamines activate PDK → PDC inhibited → pyruvate shunted to oxaloacetate via pyruvate carboxylase for gluconeogenesis.</p>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical: PDC Deficiency and Thiamine Deficiency</div>
      <p>PDC deficiency causes lactic acidosis (pyruvate backs up, converted to lactate) with neurological damage, because neurons are especially dependent on glucose oxidation. Thiamine (B1) deficiency (Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome, common in alcoholism) also impairs PDC (and α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase in TCA), producing similar lactic acidosis. Treatment: high-dose IV thiamine before giving glucose — giving glucose first to a thiamine-deficient patient worsens the crisis by demanding more PDC activity than can be supplied.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">PDC Net Reaction</div>
      Pyruvate + NAD⁺ + CoA-SH → Acetyl-CoA + CO₂ + NADH    ΔG°' = −8.0 kcal/mol (irreversible)
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq6c">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">A patient with alcoholism presents with confusion, ataxia, and eye movement abnormalities. Labs show elevated blood pyruvate and lactate. The attending gives IV glucose before thiamine — the patient worsens. Why?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq6c',this,false)">Glucose competes with thiamine for the same transporter</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq6c',this,true)">Extra glucose increases glycolytic flux → more pyruvate overwhelms the already-limited PDC → worsens lactic acidosis</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq6c',this,false)">Glucose activates PDK, phosphorylating and inactivating PDC directly</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq6c',this,false)">Glucose directly inhibits thiamine absorption from the gut</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq6c-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 7: PENTOSE PHOSPHATE SHUNT ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec7">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">07</span> Pentose Phosphate Shunt (PPP)</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Glycolysis is not the only thing cells can do with glucose-6-phosphate. The <strong>pentose phosphate pathway</strong> (also called the pentose phosphate shunt or hexose monophosphate shunt) is a side road that branches off right after step 1 of glycolysis.</p>
    <p>Instead of making ATP, this pathway makes two very important things: <strong>NADPH</strong> (a different kind of electron carrier, used to make and protect molecules) and <strong>ribose-5-phosphate</strong> (the sugar backbone needed to build DNA and RNA).</p>
    <div class="callout analogy">
      <div class="callout-label">Think of It This Way</div>
      <p>If glycolysis is your city's power plant, the pentose phosphate shunt is the water treatment plant and the factory supply warehouse. It does not generate electricity (ATP). Instead, it makes the protective chemicals (NADPH for antioxidant defense) and the raw materials (ribose for building genetic blueprints).</p>
    </div>
    <p>NADPH is especially important in red blood cells, which use it to keep an antioxidant called glutathione active. Without enough NADPH, red blood cells fall apart when exposed to oxidative stress — this is what happens in G6PD deficiency, a common inherited condition.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Products</div>
      <p>NADPH: for fatty acid synthesis, antioxidant defense, steroid synthesis. Ribose-5-phosphate: for DNA, RNA, ATP, CoA, and other nucleotides.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>The pentose phosphate pathway (PPP) branches from glycolysis at glucose-6-phosphate. It has two phases:</p>
    <p><strong>Oxidative phase</strong> (irreversible): G6P is oxidized by glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) to produce 2 NADPH and ribulose-5-phosphate (a 5-carbon sugar) plus CO₂. NADPH is the key product here.</p>
    <p><strong>Non-oxidative phase</strong> (reversible): Ribulose-5-phosphate is converted to ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleotide synthesis) or back to glycolytic intermediates (F6P and G3P) via transketolase and transaldolase reactions. This phase connects the PPP to glycolysis bidirectionally.</p>
    <p>The pathway's emphasis depends on the cell's needs. High demand for NADPH (e.g., in fatty acid synthesis, antioxidant response) drives the oxidative phase. High demand for ribose (e.g., rapidly dividing cells) drives the non-oxidative phase. When both are available but energy is also needed, intermediates cycle back into glycolysis.</p>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">G6PD Deficiency</div>
      <p>G6PD deficiency is the most common enzyme deficiency worldwide (~400 million affected). Without G6PD, NADPH cannot be made. Without NADPH, glutathione cannot be kept reduced. Oxidative stress (from infections, certain drugs like primaquine, or fava beans) damages RBC membranes → hemolytic anemia. This is actually protective against malaria — oxidative stress in G6PD-deficient RBCs kills the Plasmodium parasite.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-q" id="pq7b">
      <div class="pq-header">&#128161; Quick Check</div>
      <div class="pq-q">A rapidly dividing cancer cell needs large amounts of ribose-5-phosphate for DNA synthesis. Which enzyme is the critical first step of the pathway that provides it?</div>
      <div class="pq-options">
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq7b',this,false)">Hexokinase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq7b',this,true)">Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD)</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq7b',this,false)">Transketolase</button>
        <button class="pq-opt" onclick="checkPQ('pq7b',this,false)">Phosphofructokinase-1</button>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-feedback" id="pq7b-fb"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>The PPP is the primary source of cellular NADPH and ribose-5-phosphate. The oxidative phase is irreversible and generates 2 NADPH and 1 CO₂ per G6P. Rate-limiting enzyme: G6PD, activated by NADP⁺ and inhibited by NADPH (product). The non-oxidative phase is reversible and connects the PPP to glycolysis/gluconeogenesis via transketolase (TPP-dependent, requires B1) and transaldolase.</p>
    <p>NADPH serves multiple functions: (1) reductive biosynthesis — fatty acid synthesis (FAS, needs 14 NADPH per palmitate), cholesterol synthesis; (2) antioxidant — glutathione reductase uses NADPH to regenerate GSH from GSSG; (3) ROS production — NADPH oxidase in phagocytes generates superoxide for killing bacteria; (4) cytochrome P450 reactions in the liver (drug metabolism, steroidogenesis).</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Oxidative Phase (overall per G6P)</div>
      G6P + 2 NADP⁺ + H₂O → Ribulose-5-P + CO₂ + 2 NADPH + 2 H⁺
    </div>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Clinical: G6PD Deficiency and the Warburg Connection</div>
      <p>G6PD is upregulated in many cancers — cancer cells need NADPH for fatty acid synthesis (building new membranes) and for antioxidant defense against their own high ROS production. The non-oxidative phase also provides ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide synthesis in rapidly dividing cells. This is why the Warburg effect (aerobic glycolysis) in cancer is not the full picture — G6P also diverts to the PPP. Targeting G6PD is an active area of anti-cancer drug development.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="worked-example">
      <div class="we-header"><span class="we-badge">Worked Example</span><span class="we-title">NADPH vs. NADH — Why Two Different Carriers?</span></div>
      <div class="we-body">
        <p>NADH and NADPH are chemically nearly identical, differing only by a phosphate group on the 2' ribose of the adenine nucleotide. But they serve opposite metabolic roles:</p>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">1</span><span>NADH is produced in catabolic pathways (glycolysis, TCA) and is oxidized by the ETC to generate ATP. It is a "currency" for catabolism.</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">2</span><span>NADPH is produced by the PPP (and isocitrate dehydrogenase and malic enzyme in the cytosol) and is used in anabolic reactions. Cells maintain a high NADPH/NADP⁺ ratio (anabolic conditions) simultaneously with a high NAD⁺/NADH ratio (needed for catabolic flux). Keeping them separate prevents metabolic futile cycling.</span></div>
        <div class="we-step"><span class="we-step-num">3</span><span>Different enzyme active sites distinguish NADPH from NADH by recognizing the 2'-phosphate — a single group that routes the molecule to entirely different metabolic fates.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ===== SECTION 8: CONNECTIONS TO FULL METABOLISM ===== -->
<div class="section-card" id="sec8">
  <h2><span class="sec-num">08</span> Connections to the Full Metabolic Network</h2>

  <!-- BASIC -->
  <div class="level-content active" data-level="basic">
    <p>Glycolysis does not exist alone — it is the gateway to everything else. Pyruvate flows into the Krebs cycle (our next module), where far more energy is extracted. The NADH made in glycolysis eventually feeds into the electron transport chain to make more ATP. The pentose phosphate shunt provides building blocks. And the whole system can run in reverse during fasting — a process called gluconeogenesis — when your liver makes new glucose to keep your blood sugar up.</p>
    <p>Here is a map of the key connections. The next three modules in this series will take you through each pathway in depth.</p>
    <div class="callout keyidea">
      <div class="callout-label">The Metabolic Web</div>
      <p>Glucose → Glycolysis → Pyruvate → Krebs Cycle → Electron Transport Chain (ATP). Branch: G6P → Pentose Phosphate Shunt (NADPH + ribose). Reverse: Gluconeogenesis (rebuild glucose from non-sugar sources). Coming up: Module 2 covers Krebs, Module 3 covers oxidative phosphorylation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HIGH SCHOOL -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="hs">
    <p>Glycolysis intersects with virtually every other metabolic pathway. G6P is a central branch point: it routes to glycolysis, the PPP, or glycogen synthesis. Pyruvate branches to the Krebs cycle (aerobic), lactate (anaerobic), or gluconeogenesis precursors. Intermediates feed amino acid synthesis (3-phosphoglycerate → serine → glycine and cysteine; pyruvate → alanine by transamination).</p>
    <p>Gluconeogenesis reverses most of glycolysis using the same enzymes (the 7 near-equilibrium steps), but bypasses the three irreversible steps using glucose-6-phosphatase, fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase, and the pyruvate carboxylase/PEPCK pair. It occurs primarily in the liver during fasting.</p>
    <div class="callout mnemonic">
      <div class="callout-label">Series Preview</div>
      <p>Module 2 (Krebs): Acetyl-CoA + OAA → 8-step cycle → 3 NADH, 1 FADH₂, 1 GTP, 2 CO₂ per turn. Module 3 (Oxidative Phosphorylation): NADH and FADH₂ feed the ETC; ~32 ATP per glucose made here. Glycolysis contributes only ~7% of the total ATP yield from glucose oxidation — the other 93% comes from the mitochondria.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLLEGE -->
  <div class="level-content" data-level="college">
    <p>Glycolytic intermediates serve as biosynthetic precursors across multiple pathways. G6P feeds glycogen synthesis (UDP-glucose pathway) and the PPP. F6P and G3P are PPP non-oxidative phase entry points. 3-phosphoglycerate → serine (and thus glycine, cysteine, folate cycle). Pyruvate → alanine (ALT reaction), acetyl-CoA (PDC), oxaloacetate (pyruvate carboxylase, for gluconeogenesis and TCA anaplerosis).</p>
    <p>The overall ATP yield from complete glucose oxidation (glycolysis + PDC + TCA + OxPhos) is approximately 30–32 ATP per glucose under physiological conditions (using P/O ratios of ~2.5 for NADH and ~1.5 for FADH₂ at Complex V). Glycolysis contributes only 2 net ATP directly — the major yield comes from oxidative phosphorylation driven by the 10 NADH and 2 FADH₂ generated between glycolysis and the TCA cycle.</p>
    <div class="callout clinic">
      <div class="callout-label">Integration: Why Cancer Cells Use Aerobic Glycolysis</div>
      <p>In proliferating cells, the Warburg effect serves purposes beyond ATP: (1) G6P → PPP → NADPH for lipid synthesis and ROS buffering; (2) 3-PG → serine, glycine, one-carbon metabolism for nucleotide synthesis; (3) pyruvate → acetyl-CoA → lipid synthesis (mem­brane building). Cells that grow need carbon frames, not just energy — glycolysis provides the biosynthetic intermediates. OxPhos produces more ATP but consumes intermediates rather than feeding biosynthesis.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

